[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction: 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello everyone, I am FM Amro El Jawich from Lebanon. I am a 3-time Lebanese champion and was the youngest to achieve the feat  (at the age of 15)  . I am also a professional trainer who earned the Fide Trainer title  (FT)  . My current ELO is 2309, and I am currently working to achieve the IM title. This is my third course for Chessable, my first course being 'The Shirov Gambit: Break Down the Philidor Defense  (4.79-star rating)  and the second being 'Razor Sharp Rauser Sicilian  (4.88-star rating)  . I hope you like this course, and the others are yet to come! }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ I believe that many of you, as for me, probably heard about the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, but I never faced it on the board. The first time I saw it was in Dubai open when I had to prepare against GM Alexander Rakhmanov, one of the strongest players currently playing this variation. I lost that game, but at least it woke me up that this variation is very tricky to face. I finally concluded that the Sicilian-Nimzovich is, of course, a risky variation but is also not researched well enough and will be a big surprise for your opponent. In this course, I decided to cover two approaches for Black in the mainline. The first is full of madness where you will put your opponent in a vast tactical field filled with traps, which is the perfect situation for blitz and rapid games. Still, of course, with previous computer analysis and preparation, White might find some solutions and perhaps put us sometimes in challenging situations. That's why I also considered a second approach where we play in a quieter way where engines find it more acceptable and more suitable for classical games. According to what I said before, I had to put the lines favored by the engine as the mainline, to be completely honest with you. Still, I highly encourage you to check the variations marked as alternatives because, practically speaking, they might suit your style more and you might find that White's solutions are almost impossible to find. So let the fun begin! }
*

