[White "Quickstarter: 3.Nc3"]
[Black "QuickStarter 3.Nc3 4.Bb5+"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most played or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course, to give you a fast and general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and check the possible alternatives in the respective theory chapters. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now, you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to; for example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I already published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. Bb5+
{ The third most played move in this position. White keeps his options open regarding the e4-pawn and gives a check first. It's an interesting idea, but with correct play it should not worry us. }
4... Bd7 { The most logical-looking move and the best one. } 5. e5
{ Since our Bishop occupies the d7-square, White kicks the f6-Knight away as it can't go back to d7. }
5... Bxb5 6. Nxb5
{ As I always try to give multiple ways to continue, I believe Black can consider two continuations here, please note that the other continuation is included in the Mainline 3.Nc3 chapter   6...Nfd7?!  looks the most natural here but after  7.e6!  fxe6  8.Ng5  Qb6  9.Qe2  e5  10.c4!  Black actually might be in trouble. }
6... Qd7
{ Meeting the attack with a counter-attack. When following this concept, always be careful that your opponent's attacked piece can't run with a tempo and then capture your piece that is still under attack. }
7. Qe2 { Defending the b5-Knight. } 7... a6 { Following the same concept. } 8.
Nc3 Ng8
{ As White went back, we have to do the same. It may look strange that we have almost no pieces out, but don't worry! We have exchanged our c8-Bishop, and we might get the perfect French structure if we are allowed to play ...e6. }
9. e6
{ The only way that White isn't immediately worse is with this temporary sacrifice. }
9... Qxe6 10. Qxe6 fxe6 11. Ng5
{ White will get his pawn back as we have no way to defend our e6-pawn, but of course, this was just our extra pawn. }
11... d4 { At least we are trying to save our pawn. } 12. Nxe6
{ White benefits from the c7-fork and captures his pawn back, but he should be careful on how to save his loose Knights. }
12... Kf7 13. Ng5+ Kg6 14. Nce4
{ White manages to save his Knights, but the position is simplified and he will not be able to benefit from the development lead he had. }
14... Nf6
{ Developing and not worrying about the c5-pawn since White's g5-Knight is hanging. }
