[White "Quickstarter: 3.Nc3"]
[Black "1.QuickStarter 3.Nc3 4.e5"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most played or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course, to give you a fast and general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and check the possible alternatives in the respective theory chapters. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now, you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to; for example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I already published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. Although there is nothing to be afraid of, we must be careful not to be tricked into variations out of the scope of this course. }
4... Nfd7 5. d4
{ After this move, you probably might be thinking, why does this structure look so familiar?! Exactly, this might transpose into the French defense variations if we go with 5...e6. The real question is should we go there? Well, if you are a French defense player or you like such structures, then why not!? As for a long-time Sicilian-only player like myself, I prefer to look for something else. }
5... Nc6
{ Not committing to the French defense since we didn't play e6 yet. Also, we are threatening  6.--  6...cxd4  followed by the capture of the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxd5 { There is nothing more logical or better. } 6... e6
{ Kicking the Knight first before recapturing on d4. } 7. Nc3 cxd4
{ After this exchange, we will win back our lost pawn. } 8. Nxd4 Ndxe5
{ The rest looks simple after we got our pawn back. } 9. Be3 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4
11. Bxd4 Nc6
{ Of course, this is a simplified ending. In case you prefer more complicated positions, especially against weaker players, perhaps entering the French defense variations is a good alternative. }
