{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most played or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course, to give you a fast and general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and check the possible alternatives in the respective theory chapters. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now, you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to; for example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I already published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. exd5
{ The only way to try to play for an advantage and perhaps complicate things. }
4... Nxd5 5. Bb5+
{ The most played move in the position, developing the f1-Bishop with a check. }
5... Bd7
{ We need to be a little bit careful in the next moves. For now, although we closed our Queen's support to the d5-Knight, White can't win it as his b5-Bishop will fall. }
6. Qe2
{ The third most played move in this position. White decides to support his Bishop and is threatening to win our d5-Knight now. }
6... Nb4 { If we are running at least let's do it with a threat. } 7. Bxd7+
Qxd7 8. d3
{ Opens the way for the c1-Bishop and defends the c2-pawn at the same time. }
8... N8c6 { As White has nothing special, we can develop naturally. } 9. a3 Nd5
10. Ne5
{ The engine at first likes this move. White is going to fix his Queen on the e5-square, preventing our f8-Bishop from developing. }
10... Nxe5 11. Qxe5 e6 { Let's first take care of our d5-Knight. } 12. O-O
{ The position looks simple, but White's Queen is really annoying. Luckily, we have a strong move in: }
12... Rc8
{ To be honest, it took me some time to understand why the engine likes this move so much. After some checking, it became clear: Black is defending the c5-pawn to prepare the d5-Knight transfer via e7 followed by ...Nf5, ...Nc6, or even ...Ng6. All of these moves will fix the g7-pawn problem and Black has no issues at all. }
