{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most played or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course, to give you a fast and general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and check the possible alternatives in the respective theory chapters. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now, you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to; for example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I already published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. exd5
{ The only way to try to play for an advantage and perhaps complicate things. }
4... Nxd5 5. Bb5+
{ The most played move in the position, developing the f1-Bishop with a check. }
5... Bd7
{ We need to be a little bit careful in the next moves. For now, although we closed our Queen's support to the d5-Knight, White can't win it as his b5-Bishop will fall. }
6. Ne5
{ I believe this move is played when the White player is prepared because it needs a proper follow-up and good understanding. }
6... Nf6
{ The best continuation according to the engines. Of course, I believe in engine evaluations. Still, I also believe that some other risky move will put your opponent in practically difficult positions to find the correct replies. Thus please check the alternative move 6...Bxb5 in this position. }
7. Nxd7
{ The second most played move in this position but not the most complicated one. }
7... Nbxd7 8. d4 { Opening up the center is White's best shot. } 8... e6
{ We will just open the way for our f8-Bishop and protect our c5-pawn simultaneously. }
9. O-O
{ White doesn't want us to develop our Bishop with a tempo, so he/she just castles. }
9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 a6
{ We need to get rid of the pin before developing our f8-Bishop.   10...Bc5  is just a nightmare after  11.Qxc5! }
11. Be2 Bc5
{ After we got rid of the pin, we can develop our f8-Bishop with a tempo. } 12.
Qf4 { I will continue with a few possible logical moves. } 12... O-O 13. Rd1
Re8 { A useful move that supports the ...e5-push later on. } 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15.
Qxe4 Qc7 { Removing our Queen from the pin and preparing ...Nf6. } 16. Bf4
{ It seems that there is no better place to develop. } 16... e5 17. Bg5 Be7
{ Clearing the way for play down the c-file, and insisting on ...Nf6. } 18.
Bxe7 Rxe7
{ The position is balanced. Our next moves will probably be ...Nf6 and ...Qb6 eyeing the b2 and f2 pawns. }
