{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most played or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course, to give you a fast and general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and check the possible alternatives in the respective theory chapters. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now, you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to; for example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I already published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. exd5
{ The only way to try to play for an advantage and perhaps complicate things. }
4... Nxd5 5. Bb5+
{ The most played move in the position, developing the f1-Bishop with a check. }
5... Bd7
{ We need to be a little bit careful in the next moves. For now, although we closed our Queen's support to the d5-Knight, White can't win it as his b5-Bishop will fall. }
6. Ne5
{ I believe this move is played when the White player is prepared because it needs a proper follow-up and good understanding. }
6... Nf6
{ The best continuation according to the engines. Of course, I believe in engine evaluations. Still, I also believe that some other risky move will put your opponent in practically difficult positions to find the correct replies. Thus please check the alternative move 6...Bxb5 in this position. }
7. Qf3
{ The only real try. Other moves make our task easier. Now, White is threatening to capture the b7-pawn if we don't protect it. }
7... Qc8
{ After a long analysis, I believe that this move is the best and the most dynamic for later on.  Please note that only a few games have reached this position; therefore we will be directing our attention to the engine's favorite moves. }
8. a4
{ The second most played move in this position and the engine's favorite move. }
8... e6 { We prepare our development in the normal way. } 9. b3
{ A logical idea, going for the a1-h8 diagonal to perhaps pressure our King in the future. }
9... Be7 10. Bb2 a6
{ I prefer to force the Bishop to reveal its intentions before committing to castling my King. In this position,   10...O-O  11.O-O  a6  and now  12.Bd3  looks dangerous to me, although it was not played. }
11. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 12. Nc4
{ White correctly avoids giving us space by trading pieces and eyes the b6-square. }
12... Qb8
{ I initially believed that the move  12...b6  is a reliable alternative, but it seems that White has an energetic way to punish us. However, after the text move, we are now preparing ...Ne5 and perhaps ...b5 in the future. }
13. a5
{ A very logical move that you probably might face. The idea behind it is to stop the ...b5-push and to prepare ideas such as Na4-Nb6. }
13... Ne5 { We will maneuver our Knight into a better place. } 14. Qg3 Nc6
{ We repositioned our Knight to the preferable c6-square, and we put White in a position where he has some decisions to make. }
15. O-O-O
{ A very logical move. White is getting his King to safety before capturing any material. }
15... Qd8
{ White postponed the capture of the g7-pawn until he/she got their King to safety. We are just keeping Queens on the board, and giving him/her this opportunity of capturing the pawn again! }
*

