[Black "1.QuickStarter 3.e5 6.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most playable or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course to give you a general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and review the possible alternatives. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. White immediately challenges our f6-Knight. }
3... Nd5 { Of course, we are running our Knight straight to the center! } 4.
Nc3
{ Again, White challenges our d5-knight while developing a piece.  4.c3  is discussed in the Sidelines Chapter. }
4... e6
{ My first intention was to go with the move  4...Nxc3  , where I lost with the white pieces against Grandmaster Aleksandr Rakhmanov. However, despite finding many interesting lines and games, I couldn't find a solution for some of the engine's suggested lines. Of course, it's not wrong at all to give it a try and check some lines there, but I will be recommending 4...e6 in this book. }
5. Ne4
{ The second most played move in this position. White centralizes the Knight and prepares to kick ours by playing c4 next. I actually feel that this variation is much more complicated than the mainline. Perhaps this is why it's seldom seen. }
5... f5
{ Immediately challenging the e4-Knight. I agree this is not the move we expect to be playing in the opening, but it's the best here, in my opinion, and it's the most played also. }
6. Nc3
{ This is the most challenging move. It might look weird that White went back and forth, but now  6...--  7.Nxd5  is much more dangerous since our kingside is weakened. }
6... Nb4
{ It actually took a lot of time for me to decide on this move. I am not convinced with the moves   6...Nc6  and  6...Nxc3  which are the most played moves in this position.  6...Ne7  was recently employed by Le Tuan Minh in the Levitov Christmas Online Final against Levon Aronian, but I felt the position might be too risky. }
7. a3 { The natural reply. } 7... N4c6 { The obvious retreat. } 8. b4
{ You can't expect less from the engines. This sacrificial idea is to open the a3-f8 diagonal where White can use his a3-bishop and soon to come Nb5 Knight to paralyze our King in the center with strong pressure on the dark-squares. The most obvious continuation for me is  8.Nb5  a6  9.Nd6  Bxd6  10.exd6  Qf6  where we are doing fine, and I believe our play is easier with an obvious target on d6. }
8... b6
{ White has powerful compensation if we capture the sacrificed pawn, so let's just avoid it. Now we increase the defense for the c5-pawn and open the way for our light-squared Bishop. }
9. b5 Na5 10. h4
{ I am just showing this computer line to have a clear conscience, I don't believe that White will be able to find these moves over the board. }
10... Be7 11. d4 cxd4 12. Qxd4 a6
{ Trying to break White's control over the c6-square. We will probably castle next and continue normal development. The position is complicated yet playable. }
