{ White chooses the logical-looking move, avoiding the d4-checks and traps, but this is not the best. Actually, the White King is still in danger. }
10... O-O
{ Our response is the same as the mainline. We are defending the f7-pawn and bringing our King into safety. }
11. Qb5
{ White is correctly going for simplifications. Almost any other move could have been met with   10.--  11...d6  resembling the mainline again where either the d-file or the e-file are opened along with our c8-bishop diagonal putting White in survival mode.   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp1p1ppp/1qn5/3QP3/2B5/5N2/PPP2bPP/R1B2K1R w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ng5  is nicely met with  11...Bh4!  12.Ne4  d6!  and White is suddenly lost. }
11... Qxb5 12. Bxb5 Bc5
{ We reached an equal but playable endgame. Keep the f6-push in mind. } *

