1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. White immediately challenges our f6-Knight. }
3... Nd5 { Of course, we are running our Knight straight to the center! } 4.
Nc3
{ Again, White challenges our d5-knight while developing a piece.  4.c3  is discussed in the Sidelines Chapter. }
4... e6
{ My first intention was to go with the move  4...Nxc3  , where I lost with the white pieces against Grandmaster Aleksandr Rakhmanov. However, despite finding many interesting lines and games, I couldn't find a solution for some of the engine's suggested lines. Of course, it's not wrong at all to give it a try and check some lines there, but I will be recommending 4...e6 in this book. }
5. Nxd5 { The main move and the most serious one. } 5... exd5 6. d4
{ Preparing to open the way toward our d5-pawn.   6.c3  will probably transpose to  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3  ,  positions #20 and #21 from the Mainline 3.e5 chapter }
6... Nc6 { Developing our Knight and pressure in the center. } 7. dxc5
{ The most obvious move, immediately going after the d5-pawn. } 7... Bxc5 8.
Qxd5
{ The move that puts our variation under the test. Other options are not critical. }
8... Qb6
{ This particular variation puts us in a critical crossroad:   8...Qb6  defending our c5-Bishop and putting White in a complex situation, where he/she should be cautious about how to continue. Black has two main continuations, which are recommended in this course. The next move is trickier for White to face but if White defends accurately, we will have to defend a slightly annoying ending in the final position. Our other option is the alternative variation with 8... d6, which is favored by the engine, but it might be hard to play for a win. I decided to place the more practical ...Qb6 as the mainline, but if you feel it's not your style, perhaps you should check the alternative variation with  8...d6  . }
9. Bc4
{ I believe your opponent must be prepared to choose this move. White decides to leave the f2-pawn and be brave enough to let his King lose his castling rights. }
9... Bxf2+ 10. Ke2
{ Another brave choice, running towards the center. Other moves eliminate any hope for an advantage. }
10... O-O { Castling and defending the f7-pawn at the same. } 11. Ng5
{ White is getting excited about the direct attack on the f7-pawn, but it's brilliantly refuted, and White will resign soon if he continues with that plan. }
11... d6
{ Simple but effective. The c8-Bishop enters the game very energetically, threatening the awkward e2-King. }
12. Nxf7 { White continues with his initial idea hoping that Black falters. }
12... Be6
{ Well played! White is forced to choose between losing his f7-Knight or losing his Queen after:   13.Qxe6  Nd4 }
