[Black "4.QuickStarter Sidelines 3.e5"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this Quickstarter chapter, I tried to sum up the most playable or engine-suggested variations and shorten them as much as possible. This is, of course, to give you a fast and general idea of the whole course. Still, it's imperative to study the whole variations and check the possible alternatives. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Maybe that's the first time you hear this statement, but I believe there are no sidelines in the Nimzo-Sicilian. Perhaps you are shocked, but I had the same reaction when I intended to do a Sidelines Chapter. Simply, the already covered 3.Nc3 and 3.e5 are the most played moves in this position and are almost equally played. Then we have the King's Indian Attack with   3.d3  transposing to the Anti-Sicilians along with the Alapin transposition mentioned in the 3.e5, and what remains is a bunch of losing or nonsensical moves. I have complete trust that it will be easy for you to refute those side moves; nevertheless, I still felt uncomfortable not including a chapter covering the sidelines. Consequently, I would advise you to examine the lines, but I don't feel they need to be memorized. }
3. e5
{ You might find it weird; why am I repeating myself with the mainline chapter inside a sideline chapter? Bear with me one more move. }
3... Nd5 4. c3
{ Strangely enough that you even might not realize it at first, the position has transposed to the Anti-Sicilians Alapin variation. The usual move order would be  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)   1.e4  c5  2.c3  Nf6  3.e5  Nd5  4.Nf3  You might face this move against Alapin's usual players or funnily against players who thought c3 is a nice move, and didn't understand the transposition into the Alapin. Is that something worrying? No! is that something you need to be ready for? Yes! }
4... d6
{ Since I believe that most of the readers already have an Anti-Sicilian book  @@StartBracket@@  which you should for having a complete repertoire along with this course  @@EndBracket@@, I decided to choose some rarely but playable variations that fit with the surprise factor in this course. However, there is nothing wrong at all if you stick with your Ant-Sicilian book suggestion against the Alapin.  @@StartBracket@@Please note that if your Anti-Sicilian book chooses a move other than   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  against the Alapin then you will have to study the variations I mentioned since the transposition would not be covered in your book. Back to the line, although our move is not the most played in this position, it looks excellent and might surprise your opponent. }
5. Bc4 { The Bc4 move is expected a lot in the Alapin. } 5... Nb6
{ Running and attacking. } 6. Bb3 c4
{ Pushing the Bishop again and gaining control over the d5-square that we are soon going to use. }
7. Bc2 dxe5 8. Nxe5 Qd5 { Attacking both the e5-knight and the g2-pawn. } 9.
Qe2 { Protecting the Knight and preparing to meet   9...Qxg2?  with  10.Be4 }
9... f6 10. Nf3 Qe6
{ Forcing a completely fine endgame for us. After the Queens exchange, we will probably follow with e5 to gain more space in the center and develop our pieces. }
*

