{ Since I believe that most of the readers already have an Anti-Sicilian book  @@StartBracket@@  which you should for having a complete repertoire along with this course  @@EndBracket@@, I decided to choose some rarely but playable variations that fit with the surprise factor in this course. However, there is nothing wrong at all if you stick with your Ant-Sicilian book suggestion against the Alapin.  @@StartBracket@@Please note that if your Anti-Sicilian book chooses a move other than   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Nf6  against the Alapin then you will have to study the variations I mentioned since the transposition would not be covered in your book. Back to the line, although our move is not the most played in this position, it looks excellent and might surprise your opponent. }
5. d4 { White's first choice move in this position is supporting his center. }
5... cxd4 { We will release all of the tension in the center. } 6. cxd4 dxe5
{ Another capture. } 7. dxe5 Nc6
{ This a rarely reached position but I actually like it a lot. } 8. Bc4
{ Most of the games continued this way. Which is quite logical; White eyes the f7-pawn. }
8... Be6
{ Smartly defending our Knight and the way to the f7-pawn and bearing a nice trick in mind. }
9. O-O
{ White brings his/her to safety, and we are soon to follow. The obvious and logical  9.Ng5?  is nicely met with  9...Nc3!  10.Qxd8  Rxd8  11.Nxc3  Bxc4  where our bishop pair and the coming  Nd4  gives us a clearly better position. }
9... g6 { A Fianchetto with an e6-bishop! it actually works here. } 10. Ng5
{ Now, this move is possible. } 10... Bg7 11. Nxe6 fxe6
{ We have some questions to ask regarding the e5-pawn or the f4-pawn if it's pushed. I see this position fit perfectly with our complex and dynamic course. }
