[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mainline 3.Nc3"]
[Black "Mainline 3.Nc3 5.Bxd7+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. Bb5+
{ The third most played move in this position. White keeps his options open regarding the e4-pawn and makes a check first. It's an interesting idea, but it should not worry us with correct play. }
4... Bd7 { The most logical-looking move and the best one. } 5. Bxd7+
{ The most played move here, but it's not serious, in my opinion.  5.exd5  is met with  ...Nxd5  and a transposition }
5... Qxd7 { We are keeping the protection of the d5-pawn. } 6. exd5
{ 6.e5  Tranposes in this line } 6... Nxd5 7. d4
{ White opens the way for his c1-Bishop and creates tension in the center. }
7... e6
{ We opened the way for our f8-Bishop, and we supported our d5-Knight. We can now continue by simply following this development scheme of ...Nc6-Be7-O-O. }
