[White "Mainline 3.Nc3"]
[Black "Mainline 3.Nc3, 6...a6 alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. Bb5+
{ The third most played move in this position. White keeps his options open regarding the e4-pawn and makes a check first. It's an interesting idea, but it should not worry us with correct play. }
4... Bd7 { The most logical-looking move and the best one. } 5. e5
{ Since our Bishop occupies the d7-square, White kicks the f6-Knight away as it can't go back to d7. }
5... Bxb5 6. Nxb5
{ I always try to give multiple ways to continue; I believe Black can consider two continuations here.   6...Nfd7  looks the most natural here, but after  7.e6!  fxe6  8.Ng5  Qb6  9.Qe2  e5  10.c4!  Black actually might be in trouble. }
6... a6
{ Leaving the d7-square vacant for our f6-Knight and immediately kicking the b5-Knight. }
7. Nc3 Nfd7
{ Using the d7-square for the retreat of our f6-Knight but we must be ready for the complications after the move:   8.e6 }
8. e6
{ This might come as a surprise to you, but this is the only move for White to maintain equality as otherwise, we will play ...e6 ourselves and have an ideal French pawn structure. }
8... fxe6 9. O-O Nf6
{ White must play very accurately to maintain the compensation. Thus, I believe this is a reliable alternative when you need to play for a win. You can consider continuing with ...Qd6-Nc6 }
*

