3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. Bb5+
{ The third most played move in this position. White keeps his options open regarding the e4-pawn and makes a check first. It's an interesting idea, but it should not worry us with correct play. }
4... Bd7 { The most logical-looking move and the best one. } 5. e5
{ Since our Bishop occupies the d7-square, White kicks the f6-Knight away as it can't go back to d7. }
5... Bxb5 6. Nxb5
{ I always try to give multiple ways to continue; I believe Black can consider two continuations here.   6...Nfd7  looks the most natural here, but after  7.e6!  fxe6  8.Ng5  Qb6  9.Qe2  e5  10.c4!  Black actually might be in trouble. }
