{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. Although there is nothing to be afraid of, we must be careful not to be tricked into variations out of the scope of this course. }
4... Nfd7 5. Nxd5
{ White must already know that keeping the extra pawn is just a dream.  5.e6  we have already seen this sacrifice multiple times so it should not come as a surprise for us.  5...fxe6  6.Ng5  the most natural follow-up.  6...Nf6  improving the Knight and opening the way for the c8-Bishop to defend the e6-pawn.  7.Bb5  Nc6  both players are developing naturally.  8.O-O  e5  Black grabs some control over the center and opens the way for the c8-Bishop and can consider following with simple moves such as ...h6-Bg4-Qd6. }
