1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. Although there is nothing to be afraid of, we must be careful not to be tricked into variations out of the scope of this course. }
4... Nfd7 5. d4
{ After this move, you probably might be thinking, why does this structure look so familiar?! This might transpose into the French defense variations if we go with:   5...e6  The real question is should we go there? If you are a French defense player or like such structures, then why not!? For a long time Sicilian only player like me, I prefer to look for something else. }
5... Nc6
{ Not committing to the French defense since we didn't play ...e6 yet. Also, we are threatening:   6.--  6...cxd4  followed by the capture of the e5-pawn. }
6. Nxd5 { There is nothing more logical or better. } 6... e6
{ Kicking the Knight first before recapturing on d4. } 7. Nc3 cxd4
{ After this exchange, we will win back our pawn. } 8. Nxd4 Ndxe5
{ The rest looks simple after we get our pawn back. } 9. Be3 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4
11. Bxd4 Nc6
{ Of course, this is a simplified ending. In case you prefer more complicated positions, especially against weaker players, then venturing into the French defense variations is a good alternative. }
