1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. exd5
{ The only way to play for an advantage and perhaps complicate things. } 4...
Nxd5 5. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ White might try to chase our Queen in the center, but this should not worry us. }
6. d4 Nc6
{ I feel the position looks similar to the Sicilian Alapin if the c3-move was played, but with a pair of Knights exchanged in this case. }
7. Be3 { White supports his center. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 a6
{ It might look like a weird move at first, but this is the best choice, preventing any Nb5 jump ideas. }
9. Nxc6
{ 9.c3  it's possible for White to support his d4-knight but it will allow the Queen exchange.  9...e5  forcing the trade.  10.Qb3  White agrees to trade but on his/her terms.  10...Qxb3  11.Nxb3  Be6  The endgame is level, you can consider continuing with moves such as ...f6-a5-Kf7 but of course according to White responses. }
9... Qxc6 10. Qd2
{ I don't think that this White attempt at long castling is the right choice. }
10... e5
{ We will have the time to castle our King; therefore, we should fight in the center. }
11. O-O-O Be6 { Going for the fast ...Rc8. } 12. Qa5 Rc8 13. Rd2 Bd6
{ We will castle soon, and intend to enjoy a slight advantage. } *

