1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. exd5
{ The only way to play for an advantage and perhaps complicate things. } 4...
Nxd5 5. Bb5+
{ The most played move in the position, developing the f1-Bishop with a check. }
5... Bd7
{ We need to be a little bit careful in the next moves. For now, although we closed our Queen's support to the d5-Knight, White can't win it as his b5-Bishop will fall. }
6. Ne5
{ I believe this move is played when the White player is prepared because it needs a proper follow-up and good understanding. }
6... Bxb5
{ This was my first intention as the mainline. This path puts the White player in what I like to call a 'mission impossible' scenario with many challenging moves to find and many traps to avoid. However, with around 15 only-moves to find, I believe White objectively will keep the advantage, and Black must find a way to equalize. Thus, as I always like to keep my books very honest and clear, I couldn't suggest this line as the mainline, but as a personal opinion, I will for sure try it. }
7. Qf3 { White postpones the recapture and goes immediately after our King. }
7... f6
{ The only move to save our position, Since   7...Nf6?  Fails after  8.Qxb7  +- }
8. Nxb5 Na6
{ Of course, White is not missing   8...fxe5  since after  9.Qxd5  we are just left with worse structure and position. After our move now, the c7-square is protected, and White is under attack. }
9. Qh5+ g6
{ I agree that till now, White's only moves have been relatively easy to find, but this will not be the case for so long. }
10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qxh8 { This is all forced till now. } 11... Qd7
{ Forcing the b5-Knight away. } 12. Nc3 { The only good move. } 12... Qe6+
{ Activating our Queen and taking away White's castling rights. } 13. Kf1
{ White lost the castling rights. } 13... Nab4 14. Qh4
{ The only move to keep the advantage, smartly defending the c2-pawn with the trick of:   14...Nxc2??  15.Qa4!  Winning our Knight. Of course, this defensive idea is tough to find over the board. }
14... Qa6+ 15. Kg1 O-O-O { Almost all of Black's pieces are now in the game. }
16. Qg4+ { White tries again to defend his c2-pawn smartly. } 16... f5 17. Qd1
Bg7
{ We have finished our development with a safe King, whereas White still has some issues to solve. }
18. Nxd5 Rxd5 19. d3 Qa4 20. Be3
{ White just defended like a computer and is obviously playing for two results if he/she continues with the same level he/she defended with. You can perhaps go for this variation in blitz and rapid games, but you must be ready for the risks in the classical time control. }
*

