1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3
{ This is the most played response for White. Now you are given an option to switch to other Sicilians if you wish to. For example,  3...d6  can transpose to the Dragon, Najdorf, or the Rauzer @@StartBracket@@I published a course about it, as I mentioned earlier in the introduction@@EndBracket@@. Of course, it's not logical to suggest transposing into other systems in this course as we have something planned here. }
3... d5 { Fighting for the center immediately. } 4. exd5
{ The only way to play for an advantage and perhaps complicate things. } 4...
Nxd5 5. Bb5+
{ The most played move in the position, developing the f1-Bishop with a check. }
5... Bd7
{ We need to be a little bit careful in the next moves. For now, although we closed our Queen's support to the d5-Knight, White can't win it as his b5-Bishop will fall. }
6. Ne5
{ I believe this move is played when the White player is prepared because it needs a proper follow-up and good understanding. }
6... Nf6
{ The best continuation according to the engines. Of course, I believe in engine evaluations. Still, I also believe that some other risky move will put your opponent in practically difficult positions to find the correct replies. Thus please check the alternative variation in this position. }
7. Qf3
{ The only real try.  Other moves make our task easier. Now, White is threatening to capture the b7-pawn if we don't protect it. }
7... Qc8
{ After a long analysis, I believe that this move is the best and the most dynamic for later on. Please note that only a few games have reached this position; therefore we will be directing our attention to the engine's favorite moves. }
8. a4
{ The second most played move in this position and the engine's favorite move. }
8... e6 { We prepare our development in the normal way.. } 9. b3
{ A logical idea, going for the a1-h8 diagonal to perhaps pressure our King in the future. }
9... Be7 10. Bb2 a6
{ I prefer to force the Bishop to reveal its intentions before committing to castling my King. In this position, one game went with:   10...O-O  11.O-O  a6  and now  12.Bd3  looks dangerous to me, although it was not played. }
11. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 12. Nc4
{ White correctly avoids giving us space by trading pieces and eyes the b6-square. }
12... Qb8
{ I initially believed that 12...b6 is a reliable alternative, but it seems that White has an energetic way to punish us. However, after the text move, we are now preparing ...Ne5 and perhaps ...b5 in the future. }
13. a5
{ A very logical move that you probably might face. The idea behind it is to stop the ...b5-push and prepare ideas such as Na4-Nb6. }
13... Ne5 { We will maneuver our Knight into a better place. } 14. Qg3 Nc6
{ We repositioned our Knight to the preferable c6-square, and we put White in a position where he has some decisions to make. }
15. Qxg7
{ The greedy option, but why not!? Of course, White might avoid the risky-looking move. Thus, we will consider his/her other options too. }
15... Rg8
{ We will not be merciful here. We are going to recapture our lost pawn immediately. }
16. Qh6 Rxg2 17. O-O-O { This looks like a natural continuation. } 17... Rg6
{ We chase the White Queen, and we intend to do it again on the next move. }
18. Qe3 Ng4 19. Qh3
{ This move is not an easy choice to go for, and I believe that it must be prepared beforehand. }
19... Nxf2 { We can accept the sacrifice. } 20. Qxh7 Nxd1 21. Rxd1
{ Of course, White must act energetically to prove his sacrifice; getting back lost material leads nowhere. }
21... Qf4
{ We can keep the extra material and go with our King to safety next. } *

