1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. White immediately challenges our f6-Knight. }
3... Nd5 { Of course, we are running straight to the center! } 4. Nc3
{ Again, White challenges our d5-Knight while developing a piece.   4.c3  is discussed in the Sidelines Chapter. }
4... e6
{ My first intention was to go with the following move   4...Nxc3  , where I lost with the white pieces against Grandmaster Aleksandr Rakhmanov. However, despite finding many interesting lines and games, I couldn't find a solution for some of the engine's suggested lines. Of course, it's not wrong at all to give it a try and check some lines there, but I will be recommending  4...e6  in this book. }
5. Nxd5 { The main move and the most serious one. } 5... exd5 6. d4
{ Preparing to open the way toward our d5-pawn.   6.c3  will probably transpose to  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3 }
6... Nc6 { Developing our Knight and pressuring in the center. } 7. c3
{ This is a more solid approach from White to avoid complex positions. } 7...
cxd4 { We exchange in the center to follow with the d6-push. } 8. Nxd4
{ Unexpectedly this is the strongest recapture. } 8... d6
{ We continue as we planned. } 9. Bb5 { Developing with tempo. } 9... Bd7
{ We defend and develop also. } 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Nf3
{ Obvious attempt to target our d5-pawn. } 11... Qe7+
{ Forcing the b5-Bishop back if White wishes to keep the position more complicated. }
12. Be2
{ 12.Qe2  White can force the Queen trade.  12...Bc5  Not the only move but it's nice to have control over the d4-square.  13.O-O  a6  it's tempting to push the b5-bishop and there is nothing wrong with it.  14.Qxe7  Kxe7  we don't mind our King in the center in such situations as White has no way to punish us.  15.Bd3  h6  controlling the g5-square. We can cover our king with  Be6  at any moment and you can consider moves such as ...a5-Rhd8-d4 push at a suitable time. }
12... O-O
{ We continue by guarding our King, not caring about our d5-pawn as we have strong activity. }
13. Qxd5 { Not the most serious attempt but the only special-looking one. }
13... Rfe8 { Threatening the e2-Bishop and obviously a mate in one. } 14. O-O
{ White goes for the only option, trading Bishops. } 14... Qxe2
{ We accept this trade as our remaining pieces look much more active. } 15.
Qxd6 Bg4
{ We enjoy full compensation for our pawn. White seems to be in a troublesome position; it is hard to find a good move for them here. }
