{ Again, White challenges our d5-Knight while developing a piece.   4.c3  is discussed in the Sidelines Chapter. }
4... e6
{ My first intention was to go with the following move   4...Nxc3  , where I lost with the white pieces against Grandmaster Aleksandr Rakhmanov. However, despite finding many interesting lines and games, I couldn't find a solution for some of the engine's suggested lines. Of course, it's not wrong at all to give it a try and check some lines there, but I will be recommending  4...e6  in this book. }
5. Nxd5 { The main move and the most serious one. } 5... exd5 6. d4
{ Preparing to open the way toward our d5-pawn.   6.c3  will probably transpose to  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3 }
6... Nc6 { Developing our Knight and pressuring in the center. } 7. dxc5
{ The most obvious move, immediately going after the d-pawn. } 7... Bxc5 8.
Qxd5
{ The move that puts our variation under the test. Other options are not critical. }
8... d6
{ As I always try to avoid giving only one option, let's check this interesting alternative. We delay ...Qb6 for just one move, in this line, we sacrifice a second pawn, and we open the way for our c8-bishop. This idea should look familiar to us as we have already seen it multiple times in the ...Qb6 mainline }
9. exd6 Qb6 10. Qe4+
{ White must try to benefit from the open e-file, nothing else is better. }
10... Be6 11. Qh4
{ White smartly defends the f2-pawn and prevents our long castling. Thus it's not surprising that this is the most played move in this position. }
11... Bxd6
{ We capture one of our missing pawns back, and we ask White how he/she intends to develop. }
12. Be2 O-O 13. Bd3
{ An exciting idea from our friend the engine. White brings the Bishop back with a mate threat after castling, avoiding our Nb4 threat shown in the main variation. This variation requires an accurate reply for us to maintain our compensation. }
13... Qb4+
{ I was also surprised at first, how is this the correct way to prove our compensation?! }
14. c3 Qxh4 15. Nxh4 Bc5 { Opening the file for our rook. } 16. Nf3
{ Returning the awkward Knight into play. } 16... Rfe8
{ Activating our Rook and forcing White to castle. } 17. O-O Rad8
{ Activating the second Rook with full control over the open files. White's Bishop can go to multiple squares, but we are doing fine in all of the variations. You can consider ...Bg4 as an option in the next move. }
*

