[White "Mainline 3.e5"]
[Black "Mainline 3.e5 4.Nc3 5.Nxd5 7.dxc5 9.Bc4 10.Kd1 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5
{ The second most played move in this position. White immediately challenges our f6-Knight. }
3... Nd5 { Of course, we are running straight to the center! } 4. Nc3
{ Again, White challenges our d5-Knight while developing a piece.   4.c3  is discussed in the Sidelines Chapter. }
4... e6
{ My first intention was to go with the following move   4...Nxc3  , where I lost with the white pieces against Grandmaster Aleksandr Rakhmanov. However, despite finding many interesting lines and games, I couldn't find a solution for some of the engine's suggested lines. Of course, it's not wrong at all to give it a try and check some lines there, but I will be recommending  4...e6  in this book. }
5. Nxd5 { The main move and the most serious one. } 5... exd5 6. d4
{ Preparing to open the way toward our d5-pawn.   6.c3  will probably transpose to  6.d4  Nc6  7.c3 }
6... Nc6 { Developing our Knight and pressuring in the center. } 7. dxc5
{ The most obvious move, immediately going after the d-pawn. } 7... Bxc5 8.
Qxd5
{ The move that puts our variation under the test. Other options are not critical. }
8... Qb6
{ This particular variation puts us in a critical crossroad:   8...Qb6  defending our c5-Bishop and putting White in a complex situation, where he/she should be cautious about how to continue. Black has two main continuations, which are recommended in this course. The next move is trickier for White to face but if White defends accurately, we will have to defend a slightly annoying ending in the final position. Our other option is the alternative variation with 8... d6, which is favored by the engine, but it might be hard to play for a win. I decided to place the more practical ...Qb6 as the mainline, but if you feel it's not your style, perhaps you should check the alternative variation with  8...d6  . }
9. Bc4
{ I believe your opponent must be prepared to choose this move. White decides to leave the f2-pawn and be brave enough to let his King lose his castling rights. }
9... Bxf2+ 10. Kd1
{ It's a playable move, but I don't think it's to anyone's taste to put his/her King in such an open position. }
10... O-O { For us, we can enjoy the privilege of castling our King. } 11. Qb5
{ White logically tries to simplify the position, therefore we can call this move a logical mistake! To be honest, the moves are hard to find for White. }
11... d5 { Opening the way for the c8-Bishop with a tempo. } 12. exd6 Qd8
{ Again, we avoided the Queen exchange, and we will focus on the White's weak King. }
*

