1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Maybe that's the first time you hear this statement, but I believe there are no sidelines in the Nimzo-Sicilian. Perhaps you are shocked, but I had the same reaction when I intended to do a Sidelines Chapter. Simply, the already covered 3.Nc3 and 3.e5 are the most played moves in this position and are almost equally played. Then we have the King's Indian Attack with the move   3.d3  transposing to the Anti-Sicilians along with the Alapin transposition mentioned in the 3.e5 chapter, and what remains is a bunch of losing or nonsensical moves. I have complete trust that it will be easy for you to refute those side moves; nevertheless, I still felt uncomfortable not including a chapter covering the sidelines. Consequently, I would advise you to examine the lines, but I don't feel they need to be memorized. }
3. Qe2
{ I guess I will repeat this sentence on every sideline: Why is White choosing this move?! I just have no idea. }
3... Nc6
{ We will develop and try to benefit from the awkward Queen placement on e2-square. }
4. e5
{ This resembles the mainline with ...e5 but with a strange Queen on the e2-square. }
4... Nd5 { Let's check how the game continues if we stick to the same moves. }
5. Nc3 Ndb4
{ The same idea with the move   5...e6  is still possible here, but I prefer to start threatening stuff already. }
6. d3
{ Logically opening both ways: The c2-pawn defense and the diagonal for the c1-Bishop. }
6... Qa5
{ I like it when our opponents are forced to find the only moves in the position, and I like it more when they are even good moves anyway. White must react to the oncoming threat of ...Nd4. }
7. Be3 { The only way! } 7... d5
{ Opening the way for our c8-Bishop and threatening d4 winning a piece. } 8.
exd6 { Again, the only move! } 8... Bg4
{ We sacrificed a pawn for considerable activity. It seems that White's only way is to give the pawn back to avoid getting into deep troubles. }
