1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ Maybe that's the first time you hear this statement, but I believe there are no sidelines in the Nimzo-Sicilian. Perhaps you are shocked, but I had the same reaction when I intended to do a Sidelines Chapter. Simply, the already covered 3.Nc3 and 3.e5 are the most played moves in this position and are almost equally played. Then we have the King's Indian Attack with the move   3.d3  transposing to the Anti-Sicilians along with the Alapin transposition mentioned in the 3.e5 chapter, and what remains is a bunch of losing or nonsensical moves. I have complete trust that it will be easy for you to refute those side moves; nevertheless, I still felt uncomfortable not including a chapter covering the sidelines. Consequently, I would advise you to examine the lines, but I don't feel they need to be memorized. }
3. Bd3
{ It's not as stupid as it looks, White is preparing ideas with c3-Bc2-d4. }
3... Nc6 4. c3 d5
{ We will strike in the center and counter White's only idea. } 5. exd5 Qxd5
{ Using the fact the c3-square is not available for the White Knight and the awkward d3-Bishop to activate our Queen in the center. }
6. Bc2 { White continues with his intended idea. } 6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5
{ Keeping the annoying pin. } 8. Qe2 Rd8 9. d3 Bg6
{ White's position is cramped and Black enjoys a clear advantage. } *

