[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Perez Mitjans, Orelvis vs. Rakhmanov, Alexander Catalan League Round 1(2019)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Of course, it's not a surprise that I started the model games chapter with GM Alexander Rakhmanov. I already mentioned that he is one of the strongest players currently playing the Nimzo-Sicilian. However, don't worry; we will be seeing many different top players in this chapter. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Ne5 Nf6 7. Qf3 Qc8 8.
a4 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. d3
{ All previous moves were already considered in our theoretical chapters. Now white chooses 10.d3 instead of the move  10.b3  , which is a logical choice we should consider. }
10... O-O { Getting our King to safety before making any other commitments. }
11. Bf4
{ White continues with their logical play and develops his Bishop to the most accurate place. }
11... a6 { Very tempting move and a good one to play. } 12. Bxd7 Nfxd7
{ Not the kind of move that we normally expect. Nevertheless, Rakhmanov greatly understands the position and how important it is to have the ...Nc6-Nd4 option. The f6-square is better used with our dark-squared Bishop. }
13. Nc4 { Correctly playing for control over the b6-square. } 13... Nc6 14. a5
Nd4 { The obvious but unpreventable plan has been achieved. } 15. Qd1
{ Forced. } 15... Qc6
{ Improving the Queen, connecting the Rooks, and controlling the d6-square. Key elements in the Nimzowitsch Sicilian that'll make you more confident executing your moves. }
16. Re1
{ Very logical but not to the engine's taste.  16.Ne4  This is the engine choice.  16...Nf6  17.Nxf6+  Bxf6  Of course, it looks like nothing special. }
16... Bd8
{ A nice transfer of the Bishop.  16...Nf5  followed by  17.--  17...Rad8  was also possible. }
17. Ne4 Bc7
{ Exchanging pieces to gain some space and an easier relocation for the other pieces. }
18. Bxc7 Qxc7
{ Black's play seems obvious: Bring the d7-Knight into the c6-square and pressure the overextended a5-pawn. }
19. Ned2
{ Trying to exchange the annoying d4-Knight. The engine likes the move  19.c3  but from a human point of view, it seems to weaken the d3-pawn. }
19... Rad8 20. Nf3 Nb8 { It seems nothing can stop our other Knight also. } 21.
Nxd4
{ The engine doesn't like this exchange nor the opening of the c-file, but his suggestion of going back with  21.Nfd2  seems a bit hard to accept. }
21... cxd4 22. Qf3 Nc6 23. Qg3 Qe7 24. Qf3 Qc7 25. Qg3
{ White offers repetition. } 25... Qe7 26. Qf3 Rfe8
{ Being the higher rated and having the better position eliminates any thoughts of taking the draw offer. }
27. Qf4 Rd5
{ Another hidden benefit from the ...cxd4 capture. Not only the c-file is opened, but also the way into the a5 pawn is cleared also! }
28. Re2 Red8 29. h3 Rb5 { Inviting his other rook. } 30. Ra4 Rdd5 31. b3 h6
{ Avoiding any surprises on the 8th rank. } 32. Re4 Qd8 33. g3 Qe7
{ Inviting White to weaken their own position. } 34. h4 Rf5
{ With White holding tight into the a5-pawn by focusing on the d4-pawn, Rakhmanov saw another bright road. }
35. Qd6 Qf6 { Pieces are switching to the Kingside. } 36. f4 g5
{ I'll weaken my King but I will destroy yours! } 37. hxg5 hxg5 38. Qc7 gxf4
39. Rxf4 Rxf4 { White position collapses. } 40. Qxf4 Rf5 41. Qg4+ Rg5 42. Qh4
Qg6 43. Kg2 Rh5 { Slowly gaining control over the h-file . } 44. Qe4 Qh6 45.
Qf4 Rh2+ 46. Kf3 Qh5+
{ Rakhmanov goes for the winning endgame, the engine has another way but this seems the most human way. }
47. Qg4+ Qxg4+ 48. Kxg4 Rxc2 49. Nd6 Ne5+ 50. Kg5 Kg7
{ Perhaps many of you including me was choosing which pawn to target, but Rakhmanov has something else in mind. }
51. Nxb7 Rf2 { Threatening ...f6 followed by ...Rh2 mate! } 52. Kh4 f5 53. g4
f4 54. Nc5 Nf3+
{ White resigned before getting mated on board. Rakhmanov really showed some great technical skills in this game. }
