[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Giri, Anish vs. Kovalev, Vladislav 46th Dortmund Sparkassen Chess-Meeting (2018) "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. c3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 d6 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. O-O
{ We already looked at 11.Nf3 in our theoretical chapters. } 11... O-O 12. Nb3
{ Perhaps trying to seize some control over the c5-square, avoiding exchanges over the d4-square, and of course, threatening the d5-pawn. }
12... a6 13. Be2 Qc7
{ There is nothing wrong with this move, but it would be better if Black starts was with the move   13...Re8  keeping ideas such as ...Bb8 and ...Qc7 possible. }
14. h3 Rfe8 { The Black pieces look nicely coordinated. } 15. Re1 Re5
{ An energetic move intending multiple ideas such as defending the d5-pawn, doubling the Rooks, or even shifting the e5-Rook in some moment. }
16. Be3
{ 16.Bf4  This is of course a silly blunder.  16...Rxe2  and Black wins a piece. }
16... Rae8 17. Bd3 g6
{ 17...Qc8  I prefer this move more, keeping White worried about ...Bxh3 sacrifices. }
18. Qd2 Qd8 { Preparing ...Qh4 ideas. } 19. Nd4 Nxd4
{ Black simplifies the position with multiple exchanges where the draw is a satisfactory result for him. }
20. Bxd4 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Qe8 23. Qd2
{ White avoids excessive simplification and hopes that he can benefit from Black's isolated pawn. }
23... Be5 24. Be3 Qe6 25. f4
{ I feel this move was the beginning of White's downfall. } 25... Bf6 26. a3 h5
{ I am always a fan of putting a pawn on h4-pawn in these positions. } 27. Bc2
Bc6 { Some long back and forth maneuvers follow. } 28. Bf2 Qe7 29. Bd1 Qe6 30.
Bc2 Qe7 31. Bb6 Qe6 32. Qf2 Qe8 33. Qd2 Qe6 34. Bc5 Qe8 35. Qd1
{ When all looked simple and non-concrete White blunders. } 35... d4
{ Black smartly spots this genius move. White doesn't dare to grab the pawn. }
36. Qd2
{ White correctly avoids the capture but the position is already hard thanks to Black's very active pieces.   36.cxd4  Qe3+  37.Kh2  Qxf4+  38.Kh1  Qg5  39.Qe2  Qc1+  40.Qd1  Qxb2  White pawns fall apart thanks to the constant mating threats.  36.Bxd4  Bxd4+  37.cxd4  Qe3+  38.Kh2  Qxf4+  39.Kh1  Qg5  40.Qe2  Qc1+ }
36... dxc3 37. bxc3 Qe6 { Black prepares to attack the weak white pawns. } 38.
Bd4 Bxd4+ 39. cxd4 Qa2 40. Qc3 Qd5 41. Qd2 Qa2
{ The technique of gaining time on the clock. } 42. Qc3 h4
{ The pawn push that I like to see. } 43. Kh1 a5
{ Black comfortably pushes his pawns to better squares thanks to the hanging Bishop on c2. }
44. a4 Qd5
{ 44...Bxa4  Black's greed chasing down a pawn will give White an opportunity to give perpetual checks.  45.Bxa4  Qxa4  46.f5  When Black might have already missed the win. }
45. Qd2 b6
{ 45...Kf8  is the engine choice to prepare for ...f5, but of course, that is easy to say when you have an engine beside you. }
46. f5 { Now White can draw the endgame. } 46... Kg7 47. fxg6 fxg6 48. Bd1 Qf5
49. Kg1 Bd5 50. Bc2 Qf6 51. Qe3 g5 52. Bd3 Kh6 53. Bc2 Kg7
{ Black repeats the position but should have gone immediately with  53...Qf4  . }
54. Bd3 Kh6 55. Bc2 Qf4 { Not missing it again } 56. Qd3 Kg7 57. Qg6+ Kf8 58.
Qd3 Kg7 59. Qg6+ Kf8 60. Qd3 Ke7
{ The black King slowly escapes from the checks. } 61. Bd1 Qe4 62. Qd2
{ 62.Qxe4+  Going for the Bishop endgame when your pawns are fixed on the same color of your bishop is generally a bad idea.  62...Bxe4  63.Kf2  Kd6  64.g3  Kd5  65.gxh4  gxh4  66.Ke3  Bf5  67.Bg4  Bc2  68.Bd7  Kd6  White must abandon his h3 or a4 pawns. }
62... Kd6 63. Bc2 Qf4 64. Qd3 Kc7 65. Qh7+
{ The engine tries to hold with  65.Qc3  but of course, with 64 moves already played and time trouble, it's tough to keep defending. }
65... Kb8 66. Qd3 g4 67. hxg4 Qxg4 68. Qg6 { 68.--  68...h3  was coming } 68...
Qxd4+ 69. Kh1 Bb7 { Keeping the King safe. } 70. Qe8+ Ka7 71. Bf5 Qd1+ 72. Kh2
Qd6+ 73. Kh1 Qg3
{ White resigned as the loss of material is too much to hold. We have seen an excellent game in the isolated pawn structure coupled with a beautiful d4 break. }
