[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pohl, Walter vs. Carlstedt, Jonathan 26th Staufer-Open (2014)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
Qxd5 Qb6 9. Bc4 Bxf2+ 10. Kf1 O-O 11. b3
{ We saw in our theoretical part of the course that it's essential for White to go for   11.Qb5  and exchange Queens. However, in a practical game, it's tempting for White to develop the pieces with ideas of pressuring the f7 and g7-pawn with mating attacks, so let's see how Black dealt with White's dreams. }
11... Bc5
{ Getting the dark-squared Bishop to safety and preventing Qb5 simultaneously. }
12. Bb2
{ White is logically developing his pieces but this is just too slow.   12.Qe4  White must try to start some action with Ng5 ideas.  12...d5  However, Black can maintain a better position once he acts energetically and opens the position.  13.exd6   13.Bxd5  Nd4  14.Nxd4  Bxd4  15.Rb1  Be6  White is too exposed.   13.Qxd5  Bf5  Black's active pieces and his control over the d-file will decide the game. }
12... d6
{ We have seen this idea multiple times. Black is aware of it and is ready to activate his pieces and hunt White's King. }
13. exd6 Be6 14. Qd3 Bxc4
{ 14...Nb4  This was probably faster.  15.Qc3  Bxc4+  16.Qxc4  Qxd6  Black will include his rooks and hunt White's King. }
15. Qxc4 Rad8
{ Capturing immediately with  15...Bxd6  is possible but Black wishes to activate his a8-Rook first. }
16. d7
{ It was essential to improve the King position as fast as possible.   16.g3  Rxd6  17.Kg2 }
16... Qb4
{ The miscalculation of the dangerously looking ...Rxd7! leads Black to a Queen exchange while throwing away all of the advantage.   16...Rxd7  It seems that Black sensed some danger in accepting White's d7-pawn.  17.Bxg7  Probably what Black expected.  17...Na5   17...Kxg7  18.Qg4+  18.Qg4  It seems dangerous, but of course, the engine doesn't care and can spot the win immediately.   18.Qc3  Qb5+  18...f5  and ...Rxg7 next would have decided the game. }
17. Qd5
{ Strangely, White doesn't accept this generous gift.   17.Qxb4  Nxb4  18.Rd1  And now Black needs to be careful to hold the game. }
17... Ne7 18. Qg5
{ White wastes time and gives Black control over the important b5-square.  18.Qd3  White must keep supporting the d7-pawn and get his pieces out. }
18... f6 19. Qd2 Qb5+ 20. c4 Qxd7 21. Qxd7 Rxd7
{ Although the material is equal and the Queens are traded, but the horrible placement of the white King and his undeveloped h1-Rook will lead to a disaster. }
22. Ke2 { White hopes to get h1-Rook out in time, but it seems not possible! }
22... Nf5 23. Rhc1 Re8+ 24. Kf1 Ne3+ 25. Kg1 Nd1+
{ White lost a piece and resigned. This game shows how dangerous this variation could be if not understood correctly. Another tip is that when you are in White's position with a weak King and the possibility of getting rid of the Queens, calculate it correctly. It might be your saving chance. }
