[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kantans, Toms vs. Carlstedt, Jonathan Odense Fynsmesterskabet (2011)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
Qxd5 Qb6 9. Bc4 Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 O-O 11. Rf1 Bc5 12. Ng5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 d5 14. Bxd5
Bg4+ 15. Rf3
{ We have already analyzed the King run in the theoretical part of the course. Of course, marching the King to the center is not a satisfactory reply, so another option is for White to give some of his extra material and try to run with his King using the f1-square. }
15... Qb5+
{ Protecting the e8-Rook with tempo.   15...Bxf3+  Black has no use in capturing the Rook immediately as it gives White the extremely needed time to breathe.  16.gxf3  Rae8  17.Bxf7+  This just loses on the spot. Better is  16...h6  but still after  17.Ne4  White seems to have the upper hand with correct play.   15...Rae8  This loses in the same way after  16.Bxf7  Thus, it's now obvious that protecting the e8-rook is the key idea. }
16. c4 Rae8 { Of course, the idea was not to run away with the Queen. } 17.
Nxf7 { 17.Bxf7  makes no sense after  17...Rxf7  -+ } 17... Qd7
{ ...Rxf7 is the threat.   17...Rxe5+  Black should avoid this suicidal greedy move.  18.Nxe5+  The Rook is lost and the Queen to follow. }
18. Kd3
{ 18.Kf1  Running away from the center is worse here, actually:  18...Bxf3  19.gxf3  Qh3+  White loses the Queen on the next move. }
18... Bxf3 { As White escapes the pin, Black captures the material. } 19. gxf3
Rxf7 20. Qf4 Rf8 21. Qg4 Kh8 22. Qxd7 Rxd7
{ White reached a worse endgame after only one mistake on move 15. However, White hopes to hold this endgame with correct defense. }
23. Kc3
{ 23.Kc2  This is the correct choice we will find out why later.  23...b5  24.Bc6  Now there is no check after  24...b4 }
23... Bd6
{ 23...b5  A strong move to disturb the fixed Bishop on d5-square and also perhaps throw in a b4 check at the right moment. }
24. Be3 b6 25. h3 Re7 26. Bd4 Be5 27. Bxe5
{ White made a mistake when they were so close to saving the game.   27.b4  was better, waiting for Black to capture so White can centralize the King. }
27... Rxe5 28. a4 Rh5 29. b4 g5 30. Kd4 Rxh3 31. c5 Rh2 32. Bb7 bxc5+ 33. bxc5
Rc2
{ In general, in the endgame, the Rooks are best placed behind the passed pawn. }
34. Rd1 Rd8+ 35. Bd5
{ The game ended here. White has no good moves to play, and Black's h-pawn push will decide the game. }
