[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bodek, Michael H vs. Naroditsky, Daniel US Masters Open (2019)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bb5+ Bd7 5. e5 Bxb5 6. Nxb5 Qd7 7. Qe2 a6 8.
Nc3 Ng8 9. e6 Qxe6 10. Qxe6 fxe6 11. Ng5 d4 12. Nce4
{ We have seen in our theoretical part what happens if White captures the e6-pawn immediately, but what if White postpones the capture?! Let's examine this option. }
12... Nd7
{ Of course, the priority is to defend the c5-pawn and not the doubled e-pawn. }
13. Nxe6
{ 13.b4  The engine likes this move at first, so let's check it, so it doesn't come as a surprise to you.  13...b6  Black holds the chain.  14.Nxe6  Rc8  Again supporting the chain.  15.bxc5  bxc5  Black will hold the position but let's check this tempting move.  16.Ba3  Not the best but the only one that asks questions.  16...Ngf6  17.N4xc5  White got greedy, the pawn will cost him a lot more.  17...Nxc5  18.Nxc5   18.Bxc5  Rc6  White loses a piece.  e5  White loses a piece. }
13... Rc8 { Black defends both the c7-fork and the c5-pawn. } 14. O-O Rc6
{ Black pushes the annoying e6-Knight out for good. } 15. N6g5 h6 16. Nf3 Ngf6
{ It's time to get the pieces out. } 17. Re1 Kf7 18. d3
{ White needs to complete the development also. } 18... g5
{ Opening the way for the dark-squared Bishop,   18...e5  was also possible. }
19. b3 { White is rightly worried about the c4-push. } 19... Bg7 20. Bb2 Nd5
{ The endgame is obviously a long one, but going with   20...g4  and perhaps followed when possible with h5 was a good way to put the black pawns on the opposite color to their Bishop. }
21. h3 Rf8 22. a4 b6
{ Black doesn't want the pawn to get fixed on the b7-square. } 23. Ba3 Kg6 24.
Ned2 { White tries some maneuvers. } 24... e5 25. Ne4 Nf4
{ Both players are trying to improve their piece placement, but the position is too closed. }
26. Kh2 Rf7 27. Bc1 Nd5 28. Bd2 Bf8
{ Black aims to relocate the dak-squared Bishop. } 29. Kg3 Be7 30. Kh2 Bd8 31.
Re2 Bc7 32. Kg1 Rf8 33. Bc1 Rb8 34. Bd2 Rf8 35. Bc1 Re8 36. Ba3 b5
{ After a long back and forth, the action seems to start. } 37. axb5 axb5 38.
Bb2 { White controls the newly opened a-file first. } 38... Bb6
{ This move is not really a mistake, but it was much better to fight for the a-file with  38...Ree6 }
39. Ree1 Nb4 40. Rec1 Rb8 41. Nfd2 Rb7 42. Kf1 Ra7 43. Rxa7 Bxa7 44. Ke2
{ White needs the King to support the c2-pawn to free the Rook. } 44... Ra6 45.
Kd1 Ra2 46. Rb1 Bb8 47. Kc1 Nd5 48. g3 { Preventing the f4-jump is a must. }
48... Kf5 49. Ra1 Rxa1+ 50. Bxa1 Ke6 51. Bb2 Bd6 52. Kd1 Be7 53. Ba3 h5
{ Multiple pawn exchanges will follow. } 54. Ke2 Kf5 55. Nb1 h4 56. Bc1 hxg3
57. fxg3 g4 58. hxg4+ Kxg4 59. Na3 Nc7 60. Kf2 Nf6 61. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ The game is obviously going for a peaceful result. } 62. Kg2 Be7 63. Kf2 Bd6
64. Bd2 e4 { Black is pushing as hard as possible to trick the White player. }
65. dxe4 c4 66. Bc1 c3
{ The g3-pawn is doomed anyway, so Black pushes the attacked c4-pawn first. }
67. Ke2 Kxg3 68. Kd3 Be5 69. Ke2 Kg4 70. Kd3 Kf3
{ ...Ne6-Nc5# is a simple mating net, but the c4-pawn will fall, and then the white King will escape. }
71. Bh6 Bd6 72. Bc1 Be5 73. Bh6 Kf2 { Risky play by the black King } 74. Bf8
{ White intends to target the c7-Knight. } 74... Ke1 75. Bb4 Kd1 76. Ba5 Ne6
77. Nxb5 Nc5+ 78. Kc4 d3
{ Black's idea to breakthrough is finally on the board but White can still hold. }
79. Nxc3+ Bxc3
{ When all was quiet and simple, Black offers a great gift to the White player.   79...Kxc2  This was the only move.  80.Nd5  Nxb3  81.Ne3+  Kb2  82.Kxd3  Nxa5  83.Nc4+  Nxc4  84.Kxc4  The expected result. }
80. Bxc3
{ White throws away the gift!   80.cxd3  Bxa5  81.Kxc5  Black will not be able to hold the three passed pawns. }
80... dxc2 81. Bb2 Nxe4 82. b4 Nd6+ 83. Kc5 Ne4+ 84. Kc4
{ Draw. I agree that the game was long and full of maneuvers and slow play, but it's essential to be patient as you will face such positions in any opening you choose. Despite the closed position, both players had chances to turn the game over; alas, peace was the final result. }
