[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Lukovic, Vladimir vs. Medvegy, Zoltan BL2-Sued 1819 (2018)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Nxd5 Nxe5 6. Nxe5
{ We have seen 6.Ne3 in our theoretical part, but let's see the knights exchange in this really instructive game. }
6... Qxd5 7. Bb5+
{ White tries to benefit from his e5-Knight and develops his f1-Bishop at the same time, but he must keep an eye on his g2-pawn. }
7... Nc6
{ Even if it slightly ruins his structure, Black prefers this move over for example another option like   7...Nd7  putting himself under the pin. }
8. Bxc6+
{ A tempting move, but it's somehow bad. The retreat with   8.Nf3  was better. }
8... bxc6 9. Nf3
{ White successfully ruined Black's pawn structure, but he must suffer the outcome. }
9... Ba6
{ Logical and good but there was better.   9...g5  I usually like such energetic moves, and I like them more when the engines approve them!  10.O-O  g4  11.Nh4  Bg7  Black can exchange the doubled pawn with the ...c4-push and will enjoy a Bishop pair advantage in the open position. }
10. d3 c4
{ White plays positionally, trying to keep the doubled pawns while entombing Black's light-squared Bishop. }
11. d4
{ White plays positionally, trying to keep the doubled pawns and the closed light-squared Bishop for Black. However, this was a mistake, as proved by Black's correct response.   11.O-O  cxd3  12.Re1  This was White's best choice, but Black is obviously doing better.  12...f6  There is no need for Black to fight over a pawn that he is probably unable to keep.  13.cxd3  e6  Black will finish his development and look to benefit from his Bishop pair in this open position. }
11... c3
{ Sacrifices are not always about checkmating your opponent and sending them home. Black realizes the importance of opening the way for the light-squared Bishop and trapping his opponent's King in the center. Thus this positional pawn sacrifice is powerful. }
12. bxc3 e6
{ As we see, Black is just continuing the development normally when it will be hard for White to do the same. }
13. Be3 Bd6 14. Nd2
{ White correctly realizes that it's better to give the pawn back and go for the endgame rather than dying in the center. White intends to play Qf3 next in response to any move. }
14... Qxg2 15. Qf3 Qxf3 16. Nxf3
{ White's King is now safe, but the task remains difficult thanks to the two monstrous black Bishops. }
16... O-O
{ Of course, we know that in an endgame, there is usually no need to castle, and it's better to keep our King in the center, but here with White ideas such as Rg1 and Ng5, it makes perfect sense for Black to castle. }
17. Nd2 c5
{ Black intends to open the files for his pieces, but it was better to take things slowly with   17...Rfd8  or  17...Rab8 }
18. dxc5 Be5 19. Bd4 Bf4 20. Be3 Be5 21. Bd4
{ White is ready to collect the half-point. } 21... Bf4 22. Be3 Bb7
{ Black obviously is playing for a win and eyes the h2-pawn. } 23. Bxf4
{ An interesting sacrifice, White intends to plant the Bishop on the strong d6-square and hold the endgame.   23.O-O  Bxe3  24.fxe3  Rac8  25.Nb3  White could have gone into this simplification, but perhaps they didn't like the pawn structure at all. }
23... Bxh1 24. Bd6 Rfd8 25. f3
{ Black must have calculated this position since move ...Bb7 at least, as his light-squared Bishop barely escapes. }
25... Bg2 26. Rb1 Bh3
{ It was better to go with the f6-e5 structure immediately. } 27. Nc4
{ The c6-push is being prepared. } 27... e5
{ Black needs the Bishop's support, but obviously, the position seems going out of hand. }
28. Nxe5 Rac8 29. Rb7 f6 30. Nd3 Rd7 31. Rb4 Be6 32. Nf4
{ White leaves the a2-pawn unprotected, assuming that they can eventually trap the black Bishop. }
32... Bxa2 { Black calculates correctly. } 33. c4
{ White challenges Black with his idea to get his Bishop out as he thinks he has calculated it perfectly. }
33... Bxc4 { Black is committed to his idea. } 34. Rxc4 Rxd6
{ It's vital to calculate if the passed pawns can be stopped. } 35. cxd6 Rxc4
36. Nd5 Rd4 { The only move and what White probably expected. } 37. c4
{ It really looks that Black's Rook can't stop the d6-pawn! } 37... Rxd5
{ That was correct, The black Rook alone cannot stop the pawn, but with the use of the King, it's simply a lost pawn endgame for White. White resigned here, where I believe after missing this move; otherwise, he wouldn't go with the 33.c4 move. It was a good learning game where the 11...c3! pawn sacrifice was really instructive; after that, there were some ups and downs. Finally, Black was the one to calculate one move ahead. }
