[Black "David, Alberto vs. Magem Badals, Jordi TOP16 - FRA- PHASE 1 (2009)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
Qxd5 d6 9. exd6 Qb6 10. Qe4+ Be6 11. Qh4 Bxd6 12. Bd3 Nb4 13. O-O Nxd3 14. Qa4+
Qc6 15. Qxc6+ bxc6 16. cxd3 O-O
{ We ended our alternative theoretical line here, and I believe the position should not be hard to hold, as you will see in the game. }
17. Nd4 Bd7 { The correct move, as   17...Bd5  allows the annoying  18.Nf5  . }
18. Be3 Rfb8 19. b3 Be5
{ Black hurries to reach the opposite-color Bishops endgame, a very wise option, but there were even better circumstances to achieve it.   19...a5  Getting rid of the a-pawn will ease the task for Black.  20.Rfc1  Let's check this non-forced but logical continuation.  20...a4  21.Rab1  axb3  22.axb3  Ba3  23.Rc4  c5  24.Nc2  Be6  25.Nxa3  Rxa3  26.Rxc5  Raxb3  White can't improve when the d-pawn is blocked. }
20. Rac1 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 a5
{ Black sacrifices the c6-pawn, knowing he will get the b3 or a2-pawn after. }
22. Rc4
{ This leads to simplifications.   22.Bc5  This move seems better trying to keep the game more alive, but I am not so sure that White can improve his advantage. }
22... Be6 23. Rxc6 a4 24. bxa4 Rxa4 25. Rd6 Rxa2 26. h3 h6
{ The game appears to be heading quickly into a draw. } 27. Rc1 Ra5 28. Rc7 Re8
29. Kh2 Rd5 { Simplifying. } 30. Rxd5 Bxd5 31. Rc5 Rd8 32. Be3 f6
{ Many maneuvering attempts for White will follow but without any improvements. }
33. Rc7 Be6 34. Re7 Bf5 35. d4 Rd7 36. Re8+ Kf7 37. Rc8 Be6 38. Ra8 Bd5 39. Ra5
h5 40. h4 Ke6 41. Kg3 g6 42. Ra1 Kf7 43. Ra6 Bc4 44. Rb6 Be6 45. Kf4 Bd5 46.
Kg3 Be6 47. Rb4 Bd5 48. Rb8 Bc6 49. Rb6 Bd5 50. Bf4 Be6 51. Bd6 Bd5 52. Bc5 Be6
53. Kf4 Bd5 54. f3 Be6 55. Rb8 Bc4 56. g4
{ White aims to create a weak pawn on h5. } 56... hxg4 57. fxg4 Kg7 58. Rb6 Bd5
59. Rb8 Bf7 60. g5 fxg5+ 61. hxg5
{ This is just a dead draw. As it was thirty moves ago. } 61... Bc4
{ 61...Rd5  Aiming for ...Rf5 and ...Bd5 preventing any improvements. This was the easiest, but not the only way. }
62. Ke4 Kf7
{ 62...Rd5  It's important to stop the d5-push.  63.Rb4  Ba2  64.Ra4  Bb3  65.Rb4  Ba2  66.Rb2  Bc4 }
63. Rb6 Be6
{ The d5-push was White's only idea, but Black allowed it, most probably due to time trouble. }
64. Bd6 { The d5-push is forced, but the win is still not easy. } 64... Ra7 65.
d5 Bf5+ 66. Ke5 Ke8 67. Rb8+ Kd7 68. Rf8 Ra2 69. Rf7+ Ke8 70. Rf8+ Kd7 71. Rf7+
Ke8 72. Rb7
{ 72.Re7+  It's tough to create a breakthrough, but it's possible.  72...Kd8  73.Rg7  Re2+  74.Kf6  Rd2  75.Be7+  Kc8  76.Ke5  Re2+  77.Kd6  Kb7  78.Bf6+  White slowly pushes the Black king far away and will win with a long series of engine moves that are, of course, extremely hard to spot in time trouble. }
72... Re2+ 73. Kf6 Rd2 74. Re7+ Kd8 75. Bc7+ Kc8
{ The game is a dead draw again with all of the black pieces controlling the d-pawn. }
76. d6 Rf2 { 76...Rd1  77.Re8+  Kd7  This was an effortless draw. } 77. Bb6
{ White now gets to push the black King away and invade with his own, and he doesn't miss the chance! }
77... Rd2 78. Rc7+ Kb8 79. Ba7+ Ka8 80. Ke7 Rg2 81. d7 Bxd7
{ 81...Re2+  Black had a nice trick here.  82.Kf8   82.Be3  The winning but not easy to spot move.  82...Rxe3+  83.Kf6  Bxd7  84.Rxd7  White wins the Rook endgame.  Bxd7  Stalemate is always a strong defensive idea to use in the endgames. }
82. Kxd7 Rxg5 83. Bc5
{ The black King is cornered and is too much of a weakness, the game cannot be saved anymore. }
83... Re5 84. Kc6 Re6+ 85. Bd6 g5 86. Rh7
{ Black resigned as Rh1-Ra1 is coming. And if   86...Re2  87.Rh8  Ka7  88.Bc5  Ka6  89.Ra8#  We have seen a long game where White was obviously prepared and studied his openings,  yet he only managed to reach a deadly drawn endgame. Nevertheless, in the time trouble, Black made multiple mistakes allowing White to grab the full point. }
