1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 dxe5 8.
dxe5 Be6 9. O-O g6 10. Ng5 Bg7 11. Nxe6 fxe6
{ We have stopped here in our theoretical part. We are asking White for his e5-pawn, so let's see how a game may continue. }
12. f4 { Obviously what Black should be expecting. } 12... Qb6+
{ Black correctly uses the weakened g1-a7 diagonal on the spot. } 13. Kh1 Rd8
{ It might appear that castling should go first, but actually, White might annoy Black with   14.Nc3  Where the pressure is evident on the d5-Knight and the e6-pawn. Thus Black's choice seems the best. }
14. Qe2 { White runs from the pin to the best available square. } 14... O-O
{ As the d5-Knight is well-supported now, it seems like the right time to castle. }
15. Nc3
{ Although Black has supported his d5-Knight, White insists on being annoying. }
15... Nd4
{ Black is playing the best moves and continuing to find better squares for his pieces, starting with his c6-Knight. }
16. Qe4 { Increasing the pressure. } 16... Qc5
{ Increasing the support and attacking simultaneously. } 17. Bd3
{ Moving away and offering Black the c3-pawn. } 17... Nf5
{ Although White has compensation for the c3-pawn, it was still the best choice to go for.   17...Nxc3  18.bxc3  Qxc3  19.Rb1  Nf5  with a complex and playable game for both players. }
18. Bd2
{ The engine gives White a clear advantage after   18.Nxd5  of course, I trust the engine evaluation, but it doesn't look that obvious from a human perspective. Therefore, logically White chose another continuation. }
18... Nde3
{ Black is playing actively, opening the way for the d-Rook and trying to be annoying with his Knight. }
19. Bxe3
{ 19.Rf3  Nxg2  This is what Black perhaps intended to meet Rf3 with.  20.Rh3  I don't know if this engine move was thought of during the game, but even if it was, the position is crazy.   20.Kxg2  Nh4+  21.Kg3  Nxf3  22.Kxf3  Rd4  Black is increasing the pressure. }
19... Nxe3
{ 19...Qxe3  It seems Black was concerned about his g7-Bishop in the endgame, but the position was perfectly balanced.  20.Bc4  Qxe4  21.Nxe4  Ne3  22.Bxe6+  Kh8  23.Rf2  Rd4  Black will get his pawn back and his Bishop out. }
20. Rf3 Nf5 21. Qe1
{ Clearing the square for the c3-Knight and the way for the d3-Bishop. } 21...
Bh6 22. Bxf5 Rxf5 { Black will take the upper hand now. } 23. Qh4 Bf8
{ 23...Rdf8  Sadly Black missed this simple but very effective move.  24.Qxh6  Rh5 }
24. Raf1 Qb4 25. Qf2 Bh6 26. g4
{ Maybe this was not the best plan, but White is obviously playing to put black's dark-squared Bishop out of the game. }
26... Rf7 27. g5 Bg7 28. a3 Qa5 29. Qe2 Qc5 30. Qe4 Rdf8
{ 30...Qb6  Keeping some counterplay was important. Black can still hold the game.  31.Na4  Rd4 }
31. Kg2 b6 32. R1f2 Rf5 33. h4
{ With no counterplay, Black's task seem very hard. } 33... h6 34. b4 Qc8 35.
Ne2 hxg5 36. hxg5 Kh7 37. Nd4
{ Black's crippled pawn structure is now haunting him. } 37... Qd7 38. Nxf5
{ The rest is simple. } 38... exf5 39. Rh3+ Kg8 40. Qc4+ e6 41. Rd3 Qb7+ 42.
Kg3 Re8 43. Rd6 Kf7 44. Qc6 Qa6 45. Rd7+ Kf8 46. Rxg7
{ Black resigns. Nevertheless, there were obviously many ups and downs for both players and a lot to improve over. }
