1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8.
Qxd5 Qb6 9. Bc4 Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 O-O 11. Rf1 Bc5 12. Ng5 Nxe5 13. Nxf7 Nxf7 14.
Rxf7 Qe6+ 15. Qxe6 dxe6
{ It seems that White has reached the endgame we spoke about in our theoretical part with either previous preparation or correct calculation. So let's see how the game continued. }
16. Rxf8+ Kxf8 17. Bf4
{ White aims to get his dark-squared Bishop to the e5-square. } 17... Bd7
{ Black correctly values the importance of getting his pieces out.   17...Bd4  It might occur to you to stop White's idea. I prefer not to lose control over the d6-square because then White can annoy us.  18.Bd6+  Ke8  19.c3  Bf6  20.Bd3  h6  21.Be4  We will have trouble finishing the development of our pieces. }
18. Be5
{ White continues immediately with his plan. Nothing wrong with it, but perhaps there was a better option.   18.Rf1  White not committing his dark-square bishop is another logical move.  18...Ke7  19.Bd3  Bc6  Black can hold but probably a more challenging way than the game. }
18... Ke7
{ Black, in a brilliant way, removes his King from any checks and prepares to meet   19.Bxg7  with  19...Rg8  Where he will be winning even. I consider this move the most important one in this endgame }
19. Rf1 Bc6 20. Rf4
{ White hopes to shift his Rook and force weaknesses in Black's camp. } 20...
Rf8
{ Black offers a Rook trade in an attempt to ease up his task or causing trouble with Rf2+. }
21. Rxf8
{ Of course, White can't allow Black's rook to enter the second rank. } 21...
Kxf8 22. g3 Kf7 { The rest is simple. } 23. c3 g5 24. g4 h6 25. b4 Be7 26. Ke3
Bf6 27. Bd4 b6 28. Bb3 Ke7 29. Bxf6+ Kxf6 30. a3 Ke5
{ Black is trying to take advantage of the fact that the g4-pawn is fixed on the same color as White's Bishop. }
31. Bc2 Bb5 32. Bb3 Bf1 33. Bc2 Bc4 34. Bd1 Bf1 35. Bc2
{ White doesn't allow Black to push forward with his King fixed on the e3-square. }
35... Kd5 36. Bb3+ Bc4
{ Black tries his last trick. However, Black's King is obviously faster, so it's hard to trick the White player into the losing pawn endgame. }
37. Bc2 Ba2 38. Bd3 Bb3 39. Be2 Bc4
{ With no way for improvement from both players, a draw was agreed. } *

